<paragraph blockId="126.[670,1199,845,1763]" pageId="126" pageNumber="126">
IDENTIFICATION: As currently defined (
<bibRefCitation author="Koopman, K. F." box="[678,893,934,957]" editor="D. E. Wilson &amp; D. M. Reeder" journalOrPublisher="Washington, DC: Smithson. Inst. Press" pageId="126" pageNumber="126" refId="ref96667" refString="1993. Order Chiroptera. In D. E. Wilson and D. M. Reeder (eds.), Mammal species of the World, a taxonomic and geographic reference, 2 nd ed.: 137 - 241. Washington, DC: Smithson. Inst. Press." title="Order Chiroptera" type="book" volumeTitle="Mammal species of the World, a taxonomic and geographic reference, 2 nd" year="1993">Koopman, 1993</bibRefCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1900" box="[925,1077,934,957]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Vampyressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="126" pageNumber="126" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[925,1077,934,957]" italics="true" pageId="126" pageNumber="126">Vampyressa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
includes three subgenera and five species: 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="126" pageNumber="126">Metavampyressa</emphasis>
(including 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peterson" authorityYear="1968" box="[912,986,993,1016]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Vampyressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="126" pageNumber="126" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brocki">
<emphasis box="[912,986,993,1016]" italics="true" pageId="126" pageNumber="126">brocki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1909" box="[1062,1181,993,1016]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Vampyressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="126" pageNumber="126" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nymphaea">
<emphasis box="[1062,1181,993,1016]" italics="true" pageId="126" pageNumber="126">nymphaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1900" box="[670,812,1023,1046]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Vampyressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="126" pageNumber="126" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[670,812,1023,1046]" italics="true" pageId="126" pageNumber="126">Vampyressa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(including 
<taxonomicName box="[952,1039,1023,1046]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Vampyressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="126" pageNumber="126" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="melissa">
<emphasis box="[952,1039,1023,1046]" italics="true" pageId="126" pageNumber="126">melissa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1102,1181,1023,1046]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Vampyressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="126" pageNumber="126" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pusilla">
<emphasis box="[1102,1181,1023,1046]" italics="true" pageId="126" pageNumber="126">pusilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1900" box="[721,871,1053,1076]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Vampyriscus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="126" pageNumber="126" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[721,871,1053,1076]" italics="true" pageId="126" pageNumber="126">Vampyriscus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(including 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Spix" baseAuthorityYear="1823" box="[1011,1087,1053,1076]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Tonatia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="126" pageNumber="126" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bidens">
<emphasis box="[1011,1087,1053,1076]" italics="true" pageId="126" pageNumber="126">bidens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
only). In part because of confusion in the literature regarding middorsal stripes in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1900" box="[1003,1145,1113,1136]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Vampyressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="126" pageNumber="126" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1003,1145,1113,1136]" italics="true" pageId="126" pageNumber="126">Vampyressa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see discussion below), unambiguous identifications must still be based on 
<bibRefCitation author="Peterson, R. L. &amp; J. R. Tamsitt" bookContentInfo="7 pp." box="[995,1197,1172,1195]" journalOrPublisher="Ontario Mus. Life Sci. Occas. Pap. 12" pageId="126" pageNumber="126" refId="ref99278" refString="Peterson, R. L., and J. R. Tamsitt 1968. A new species of bat of the genus Sturnira (family Phyllostomatidae) from northwestern South America. R. Ontario Mus. Life Sci. Occas. Pap. 12: 7 pp." title="A new species of bat of the genus Sturnira (family Phyllostomatidae) from northwestern South America. R" type="book" year="1968">Petersonâ€™s (1968)</bibRefCitation>
review, which included a key (subsequently reproduced by 
<bibRefCitation author="Lewis, S. E. &amp; D. E. Wilson" bookContentInfo="5 pp." box="[849,1143,1232,1255]" journalOrPublisher="Mamm. Species 292" pageId="126" pageNumber="126" refId="ref97117" refString="Lewis, S. E., and D. E. Wilson 1987. Vampyressa pusilla. Mamm. Species 292: 5 pp." title="Vampyressa pusilla" type="book" year="1987">Lewis and Wilson, 1987</bibRefCitation>
). Information about specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peterson" authorityYear="1968" box="[1034,1143,1262,1285]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Vampyressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="126" pageNumber="126" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brocki">
<emphasis box="[1034,1052,1262,1285]" italics="true" pageId="126" pageNumber="126">V</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1069,1143,1262,1285]" italics="true" pageId="126" pageNumber="126">brocki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
collected after 1968 can be found in 
<bibRefCitation author="Baker, R. J. &amp; H. H. Genoways" editor="S. California Acad" journalOrPublisher="Sci." pageId="126" pageNumber="126" pagination="54" part="71" refId="ref91418" refString="Baker, R. J., and H. H. Genoways 1972. The phyllostomatid bat, Vampyressa brocki, in Colombia. Bull. S. California Acad. Sci. 71: 54." title="The phyllostomatid bat, Vampyressa brocki" type="journal article" volumeTitle="Colombia. Bull" year="1972">Baker and Genoways (1972)</bibRefCitation>
, Swanepoel and 
<bibRefCitation author="Genoways, H. H. &amp; S. L. Williams" journalOrPublisher="Ann. Carnegie Mus." pageId="126" pageNumber="126" pagination="323 - 335" part="48" refId="ref93773" refString="Genoways, H. H., and S. L. Williams 1979. Records of bats (Mammalia: Chiroptera) from Suriname. Ann. Carnegie Mus. 48: 323 - 335." title="Records of bats (Mammalia: Chiroptera) from Suriname" type="journal article" year="1979">Genoways (1979)</bibRefCitation>
, and 
<bibRefCitation author="Williams, S. L. &amp; H. H. Genoways" journalOrPublisher="Ann. Carnegie Mus." pageId="126" pageNumber="126" pagination="213 - 236" part="49" refId="ref102406" refString="Williams, S. L., and H. H. Genoways 1980 a. Results of the Alcoa Foundation-Suriname Expeditions. II. Additional records of bats (Mammalia: Chiroptera) from Suriname. Ann. Carnegie Mus. 49: 213 - 236." title="Results of the Alcoa Foundation-Suriname Expeditions. II. Additional records of bats (Mammalia: Chiroptera) from Suriname" type="journal article" year="1980">Williams and Genoways (1980a)</bibRefCitation>
. No subspecies of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peterson" authorityYear="1968" box="[990,1098,1381,1405]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Vampyressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="126" pageNumber="126" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brocki">
<emphasis box="[990,1008,1382,1405]" italics="true" pageId="126" pageNumber="126">V</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1024,1098,1382,1405]" italics="true" pageId="126" pageNumber="126">brocki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are currently recognized (Koopman, 1994).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="126.[670,1199,845,1763]" pageId="126" pageNumber="126">
Our voucher material, apparently the largest series of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peterson" authorityYear="1968" box="[824,1051,1471,1494]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Vampyressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="126" pageNumber="126" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brocki">
<emphasis box="[824,1051,1471,1494]" italics="true" pageId="126" pageNumber="126">Vampyressa brocki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
collected at a single locality, conforms in all respects with 
<bibRefCitation author="Peterson, R. L. &amp; J. R. Tamsitt" bookContentInfo="7 pp." box="[735,944,1531,1554]" journalOrPublisher="Ontario Mus. Life Sci. Occas. Pap. 12" pageId="126" pageNumber="126" refId="ref99278" refString="Peterson, R. L., and J. R. Tamsitt 1968. A new species of bat of the genus Sturnira (family Phyllostomatidae) from northwestern South America. R. Ontario Mus. Life Sci. Occas. Pap. 12: 7 pp." title="A new species of bat of the genus Sturnira (family Phyllostomatidae) from northwestern South America. R" type="book" year="1968">Petersonâ€™s (1968)</bibRefCitation>
original description. Although our measurement data broadly overlap those previously reported for the species, some Paracou specimens are slightly smaller than any hitherto reported in the literature.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="126.[670,1199,845,1763]" lastBlockId="128.[94,623,830,1763]" lastPageId="128" lastPageNumber="128" pageId="126" pageNumber="126">
Petersonâ€™s original description of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peterson" authorityYear="1968" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Vampyressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="126" pageNumber="126" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brocki">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="126" pageNumber="126">Vampyressa brocki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was not ambiguous, but discrepÂ­ ant readings are current in the literature. Thus, 
<bibRefCitation author="Williams, S. L. &amp; H. H. Genoways" box="[166,548,860,883]" journalOrPublisher="Ann. Carnegie Mus." pageId="128" pageNumber="128" pagination="213 - 236" part="49" refId="ref102406" refString="Williams, S. L., and H. H. Genoways 1980 a. Results of the Alcoa Foundation-Suriname Expeditions. II. Additional records of bats (Mammalia: Chiroptera) from Suriname. Ann. Carnegie Mus. 49: 213 - 236." title="Results of the Alcoa Foundation-Suriname Expeditions. II. Additional records of bats (Mammalia: Chiroptera) from Suriname" type="journal article" year="1980">Williams and Genoways (1980a)</bibRefCitation>
stated that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peterson" authorityYear="1968" box="[146,253,889,912]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Vampyressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="128" pageNumber="128" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brocki">
<emphasis box="[146,164,889,912]" italics="true" pageId="128" pageNumber="128">V</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[179,253,889,912]" italics="true" pageId="128" pageNumber="128">brocki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lacks a middorsal stripe, citing Peterson as their authority, whereas other authors have evidently interpreted Peterson to mean that a stripe is present in this species (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation author="Lewis, S. E. &amp; D. E. Wilson" bookContentInfo="5 pp." box="[171,492,1006,1029]" journalOrPublisher="Mamm. Species 292" pageId="128" pageNumber="128" refId="ref97117" refString="Lewis, S. E., and D. E. Wilson 1987. Vampyressa pusilla. Mamm. Species 292: 5 pp." title="Vampyressa pusilla" type="book" year="1987">Lewis and Wilson, 1987</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Peterson, R. L. &amp; J. R. Tamsitt" bookContentInfo="7 pp." journalOrPublisher="Ontario Mus. Life Sci. Occas. Pap. 12" pageId="128" pageNumber="128" refId="ref99278" refString="Peterson, R. L., and J. R. Tamsitt 1968. A new species of bat of the genus Sturnira (family Phyllostomatidae) from northwestern South America. R. Ontario Mus. Life Sci. Occas. Pap. 12: 7 pp." title="A new species of bat of the genus Sturnira (family Phyllostomatidae) from northwestern South America. R" type="book" year="1968">Peterson (1968: 1)</bibRefCitation>
himself clearly stated that the holotype of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peterson" authorityYear="1968" box="[221,295,1065,1088]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Vampyressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="128" pageNumber="128" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brocki">
<emphasis box="[221,295,1065,1088]" italics="true" pageId="128" pageNumber="128">brocki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is â€˜â€˜greyish brown above with a faint indistinct dorsal whitish stripe.â€™â€™ A diagrammatic character summary accompanying the original description (op. cit.: fig. 6), however, does not distinguish between the faint middorsal stripe of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peterson" authorityYear="1968" box="[383,457,1212,1235]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Vampyressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="128" pageNumber="128" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brocki">
<emphasis box="[383,457,1212,1235]" italics="true" pageId="128" pageNumber="128">brocki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the much brighter markings of two other congeners (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1909" box="[103,222,1271,1294]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Vampyressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="128" pageNumber="128" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nymphaea">
<emphasis box="[103,222,1271,1294]" italics="true" pageId="128" pageNumber="128">nymphaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Spix" baseAuthorityYear="1823" box="[285,361,1271,1294]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Tonatia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="128" pageNumber="128" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bidens">
<emphasis box="[285,361,1271,1294]" italics="true" pageId="128" pageNumber="128">bidens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4545162" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4545162" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4545162/files/figure.png" pageId="127" pageNumber="127" startId="127.[154,192,1557,1578]" targetBox="[219,1142,208,1536]" targetPageId="127">
<paragraph blockId="127.[128,1233,1557,1685]" pageId="127" pageNumber="127">
Fig. 51. LeafÂ­tent roost of the type inhabited by 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peters" authorityYear="1866" box="[692,915,1558,1579]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Uroderma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="127" pageNumber="127" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bilobatum">
<emphasis box="[692,915,1558,1579]" italics="true" pageId="127" pageNumber="127">Uroderma bilobatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in a wet opening in swampy primary forest at Paracou. This simple conical shelter, made by cutting the midrib of a 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Strelitziaceae" genus="Phenakospermum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Zingiberales" pageId="127" pageNumber="127" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="guyannense">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="127" pageNumber="127">Phenakospermum guyannense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
frond (arrow), was unoccupied when we found it, but an identical tent nearby contained three bats. Because it is difficult to approach such roosts without alarming the inhabitants, we found many empty tents that might have contained bats only moments before.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="128.[94,623,830,1763]" pageId="128" pageNumber="128">Our Paracou vouchers have a middorsal stripe, but it is extremely faint and is visible only when the dry dorsal pelage is carefully brushed. The stripe is hard to see under any conditions because it is only slightly paler than the surrounding fur, and it becomes quite invisible when the fur is wet (precluding observation in alcoholÂ­preserved specimens).</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="128.[94,623,830,1763]" lastBlockId="128.[670,1199,830,1575]" pageId="128" pageNumber="128">
Because the dorsal stripe is hard to see, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peterson" authorityYear="1968" box="[94,324,1593,1616]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Vampyressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="128" pageNumber="128" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brocki">
<emphasis box="[94,324,1593,1616]" italics="true" pageId="128" pageNumber="128">Vampyressa brocki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
externally resembles 
<taxonomicName class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Vampyressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="128" pageNumber="128" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pusilla">
<emphasis box="[597,615,1593,1616]" italics="true" pageId="128" pageNumber="128">V</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[94,173,1623,1646]" italics="true" pageId="128" pageNumber="128">pusilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with which it might be confused in the field. The latter species entirely lacks a dorsal stripe and shares several traits with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peterson" authorityYear="1968" box="[94,168,1711,1734]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Vampyressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="128" pageNumber="128" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brocki">
<emphasis box="[94,168,1711,1734]" italics="true" pageId="128" pageNumber="128">brocki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, including small size, two pairs of lower incisors, and absence of m3 (
<bibRefCitation author="Peterson, R. L. &amp; J. R. Tamsitt" bookContentInfo="7 pp." box="[513,733,830,1763]" journalOrPublisher="Ontario Mus. Life Sci. Occas. Pap. 12" pageId="128" pageNumber="128" refId="ref99278" refString="Peterson, R. L., and J. R. Tamsitt 1968. A new species of bat of the genus Sturnira (family Phyllostomatidae) from northwestern South America. R. Ontario Mus. Life Sci. Occas. Pap. 12: 7 pp." title="A new species of bat of the genus Sturnira (family Phyllostomatidae) from northwestern South America. R" type="book" year="1968">Peterson, 1968</bibRefCitation>
). Characters that unambiguously distinguish 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peterson" authorityYear="1968" box="[746,820,860,883]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Vampyressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="128" pageNumber="128" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brocki">
<emphasis box="[746,820,860,883]" italics="true" pageId="128" pageNumber="128">brocki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[889,968,860,883]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Vampyressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="128" pageNumber="128" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pusilla">
<emphasis box="[889,968,860,883]" italics="true" pageId="128" pageNumber="128">pusilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
include a suite of craniodental features (op. cit.), of which the most useful include: (1) form of the inner upper incisors (tapering to a point in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peterson" authorityYear="1968" box="[1117,1191,950,973]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Vampyressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="128" pageNumber="128" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brocki">
<emphasis box="[1117,1191,950,973]" italics="true" pageId="128" pageNumber="128">brocki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, bilobed in 
<taxonomicName box="[800,879,980,1003]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Vampyressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="128" pageNumber="128" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pusilla">
<emphasis box="[800,879,980,1003]" italics="true" pageId="128" pageNumber="128">pusilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), (2) shape of the anterior lower premolar (lowÂ­crowned and bladelike in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peterson" authorityYear="1968" box="[705,779,1040,1063]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Vampyressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="128" pageNumber="128" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brocki">
<emphasis box="[705,779,1040,1063]" italics="true" pageId="128" pageNumber="128">brocki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with higher crown and spearlike anterior cusp in 
<taxonomicName box="[861,940,1070,1093]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Vampyressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="128" pageNumber="128" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pusilla">
<emphasis box="[861,940,1070,1093]" italics="true" pageId="128" pageNumber="128">pusilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and (3) shape of the nasal aperture (with straight ventral border in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peterson" authorityYear="1968" box="[670,744,1130,1153]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Vampyressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="128" pageNumber="128" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brocki">
<emphasis box="[670,744,1130,1153]" italics="true" pageId="128" pageNumber="128">brocki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, VÂ­shaped ventral border in 
<taxonomicName box="[1102,1181,1130,1153]" class="Mammalia" family="Phyllostomidae" genus="Vampyressa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="128" pageNumber="128" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pusilla">
<emphasis box="[1102,1181,1130,1153]" italics="true" pageId="128" pageNumber="128">pusilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). The latter character is visible only on cleaned skulls, but the distinction is unambiguous and provides a means of unequivocally identifying old individuals with worn or broken teeth.
</paragraph>
